---
title: Mimi’s Coastal Fish Curry with Green Beans
description: This dish is inspired by Mimi’s time on the Indian coast. It’s a delicate, fresh tasting little number that will transport your taste buds to the village of Varkala in southern India! Traditional Indian fish dishes often involve marinating for several hours but we’ve used some HelloFresh magic to whip this one up in just half an hour, using a Bang Curry Spice - enjoy!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/55faed5379a23c380d8b4567.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/55faed5379a23c380d8b4567.pdf
time required: 30 minutes
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/mimis-coastal-fish-curry-55faed5379a23c380d8b4567
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
course: main course
cuisine: Indian
nutrition:
  calories: 713 kcal
  fat: 21 g
  saturated fat: 17 g
  carbohydrates: 101 g
  protein: 33 g
---

Boil 350ml water in a #pan with the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} for the rice. Chop
each @tilapia fillet{2} into three and put in a #bowl with the juice of half the
@lime{1/2} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}.

> If the fillets have split already and you end up with them being cut into
> more than three pieces that's fine, you just don't want them too tiny.

Now you need to get all your chopping done! Peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled
and diced) into roughly 1cm pieces. Then peel and finely chop the
@garlic clove{1}(peeled and finely chopped) and the @ginger{1}(peeled and finely
chopped). Trim the tops and bottoms off the @green beans{1} and cut them into
three, setting them aside for later.

Once your water is boiling, add your @basmati rice{1}. Cover the pan with a #lid
and leave on a low heat for ~{10%minutes}. After ~{10%minutes} remove the pan
from the heat and leave to rest for a further ~{10%minutes}.

> If you end up having to leave the rice off the heat for longer than 10 mins
> don't panic, it will be fine!

Add @olive oil{1%tbsp} to a pan and add the @mustard seeds{1}. Once they begin
to make a spluttering sound add the onion, garlic and ginger. Cook on a low
heat for ~{5%minutes} until the onion is soft. Add the @Bang Curry Spice{1} and
cook for ~{2%minutes}.

> If you want your curry mild just add half the spice mix.

> If you leave the mustard seeds for too long on their own they'll start
> jumping out of the pan, so make sure to only heat them for 20 seconds before
> you add the rest!

Pour in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, 100ml water and stir everything together.
Allow it to bubble away steadily while you get on with the beans.

Put a #pot of water on to boil with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Once it is boiling
add the beans and cook for about ~{5%minutes}. Drain and set aside the beans.

When the rice is about 4 mins from being ready, add the fish to the sauce,
gently covering it. Put the #lid on the curry and cook for ~{4%minutes} on a
low heat. Add the beans to the curry and gently stir them in, being careful of
the fish.

> Do not stir it or all the lovely pieces of fish will break up.

Serve a generous heap of rice with the delicious curry, making sure everyone
gets lashings of the lovely, flavoursome sauce.